[0.073, "o", "\u001b[H\n\n\n\n\n \u001b[1;38;2;255;68;68mgodshellÔØ» \u001b[0m\u001b[38;2;204;204;204mMost activity looks user-driven, but two items deserve scrutiny: AntigravityÔÇÖs language server is the loudest\u001b[m       \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mnetwork talker, and there was very recent local compilation/execution activity. Evidence: summary shows PID 4402\u001b[m              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m/usr/lib/antigravity/extensions/antigravity/bin/language_server_linux_x64 at 24.5% CPU, 888408 KB RAM, 52194 connections\u001b[m      \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mwith 38746 to 1.1.1.1:853 and 13448 HTTPS, plus 6684 opens on /home/raul/Desktop/projects/godshell/godshelldemo.cast;\u001b[m         \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204msummary also shows recent exits gcc/cc1/as/ld/collect2 followed by mv/rm/zsh_copy.\u001b[0m                                            \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mActive custom binaries are expected but worth tracking, not immediately malicious. Evidence: summary shows ./godshell\u001b[m         \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mrunning as PID 257989 under /usr/bin/zsh ÔåÆ /usr/bin/asciinema with 12 HTTPS connections, and another ./godshell PID 250968\u001b[m    \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204munder zsh with minor activity; summary also shows /usr/bin/sudo PID 250891 under zsh and /tmp/daemon.log opened by parent\u001b[m     \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mzsh PID 250889.\u001b[0m                                                                                                               \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mNo obvious rogue daemon or strange persistence path is visible in this snapshot. Evidence: summaryÔÇÖs active groups are\u001b[m        \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mdominated by Electron/Chrome/Firefox/systemd/desktop components; network patterns heavily center on 1.1.1.1:853 and generic\u001b[m   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mHTTPS; recently exited items are mostly shell churn, logger, hyprctl, and compilation tools.\u001b[0m                                  \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204m\u001b[0m                                                                                                                              \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mIf you want, I can drill into 1) PID 4402 lineage/network/env, 2) the godshell processes, or 3) recent shell history for\u001b[m      \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;204;204;204mraul.\u001b[0m                                                                                                                         \u001b[K\r\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \u001b[1;38;2;0;255;136mÔØ» \u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;240ma\u001b[0m\u001b[38;5;240msk godshell something...\u001b[0m                                                                                                   \u001b[K\r\n \u001b[38;2;85;85;85mCtrl+([r]efresh [s]ave [l]oad [p]anel) type help for more info, Esc to toggle focus\u001b[0m                                           \u001b[K\r\n                                                                                                                               \u001b[K\u001b[J\u001b[33;H"]
